      ###Vegetable intake on health study

    ##The following can be considered direct input into the Stata command box
. label variable id "Participant identification number"
. label variable sex "Sex"
. label variable age "Age"
. label variable genhlth "General health rating"
. label variable reggp "Has regular GP"
. label variable vegwk "Total vegetable serves per week"
. label define sex_lbl 1 "Male" 2 "Female"
. label define genhlth_lbl 1 "Excellent" 2 "Very good" 3 "Good" 4 "Fair" 5 "Poor"
. label define reggp_lbl 0 "No" 1 "Yes"
. label value sex sex_lbl
. label value genhlth genhlth_lbl
. label value reggp reggp_lbl
  ##Comment: The objective of the preface commands is to label binary and categorical data, which will allow the workflow to be easily understood as the analysis is being conducted. ‘sex’ and ‘reggp’ are binary variables and ‘genhlth’ is a categorical variable.
. summarize vegwk, detail
. histogram vegwk, width(2.5) start(0) frequency normal
. summarize reggp, detail
. codebook reggp
    ##Comment: The goal is to characterise the data of ‘vegwk’ and ‘reggp’. For ‘vegwk’, a histogram and summary statistics demonstrate that this is normally distributed data. ‘Reggp’ is binary data, therefore, observing the codebook output provides useful information into the distribution and spread of participant categories.
. histogram vegwk, by(, subtitle(Vegetable serves per week for those with or without regular GP)) by(reggp)
. regress vegwk i.reggp
    ##Comment: The first part will create a histogram that contrasts the regular GP group from the non-regular GP group and to describe it. The second line will perform a simple linear regression on vegetable serves in a week on regular GP status.
. regress vegwk i.sex age i.genhlth i.reggp
    ##Comment: sex, general health rating and having a regular GP require a dummy variable to be coded in the regression model, as they are either binary or categorical variables. For this example, we use “Male” as a reference point for sex, “Excellent” as a reference point for general health rating, and “No” as a reference point for having a regular GP.
Optional:
. pwcorr vegwk sex age genhlth reggp, sig
. regress vegwk i.sex age ib5.genhlth i.reggp
    ##Comment: The first line can be used as supplement to understand the Pearson’s correlation coefficients between the ‘vegwk’ and the explanatory variables. The second line can be used to have a health rating of 5 (Poor) as the reference point to avoid negative coefficients.

      ###Computer use and Vitamin D levels study

    ##Assigning meaningful labels and definitions to variables
label variable id "Participant identification number"
label variable vitd "Serum Vitamin D, nmol/L"
label variable comp "Recreational computer use"
label variable age "Age in years"
label variable sex "Sex"
label variable pedu "Highest parent education level"
label variable act "Physical activity in the past 7 days"
label variable pind "Family disadvantage level index"
label define comp_lbl 0 "No" 1 "Yes"
label define sex_lbl 1 "Male" 2 "Female"
label define pedu_lbl 1 "Did not complete high school" 2 "High school" 3 "Higher education"
label define act_lbl 0 "No" 1 "Yes"
label value sex sex_lbl
label value comp comp_lbl
label value pedu pedu_lbl
label value act act_lbl

####1.2 Building a multiple linear regression model with evidence
## Assessment of outliers
scatter vitd pind || lfit vitd pind, title("Distribution of vitamin D on Family disadvantage level index") leg(off)
## Assessment of and missing entries
summarize
mvpatterns
list if pedu ==. | pind ==.
## Creating new vitd variable by removing outlier, and confirming removal of single observation
generate vitd_clean = vitd if vitd <120
summarize vitd_clean, d

#### 1.2.2 Univariate simple linear regressions
## Model 0 to 5. Model 0 is not used in this analysis
regress vitd_clean i.comp ** Model 0 ** 
regress vitd_clean age *** Model 1 **
regress vitd_clean i.sex ** Model 2 **
regress vitd_clean i.pedu ** Model 3 **
regress vitd_clean i.act ** Model 4 ** - was dropped from further analysis
regress vitd_clean pind ** Model 5 **

#### 1.2.3 Multiple linear regression base model with variance inflation factors (VIF)
## Model 6
regress vitd_clean i.comp age i.sex i.pedu pind
testparm i.pedu
estat vif

#### 1.2.4 Assessment of effect modification and confounding 
## Model 7
regress vitd_clean i.comp age i.sex i.pedu i.act pind i.comp#age i.comp#sex
testparm i.comp#age
testparm i.comp#sex
## Model 8
regress vitd_clean i.comp age i.sex i.pedu i.act pind i.comp#age 
testparm i.comp#age
## Model 9
regress vitd_clean i.comp age i.sex pind // Take the difference of 'Recreational computer use' parameter estimates in model 6 and model 9
## Absolute difference calculation
display (-3.476609 - (-3.234495))
** Percent difference calculation
display (-3.476609 - (-3.234495))/3.476609*100
 
#### 1.3.1 The final model
regress vitd_clean i.comp age i.sex i.pedu pind

#### 1.3.2 Assessment of model assumptions
## Predicting fitted values
Predict yhat, xb
## Predicting jackknife residuals
Predict rjack, rstudent
## Predicting cooks distances
Predict cooksd, cooksd
## Predicting residuals
Predict res, residuals
## Fulfilling assumptions
## Cooks distances distribution
dotplot cooksd, title("Predicted cooks distances")
## Homoscedasticity assumption
scatter rjack yhat || lfit rjack yhat, leg(off) title("Jackknife residuals over predicted fitted values")
## Linearity assumption
scatter rjack pind || lfit rjack pind, leg(off) title("Jackknife residuals over family disadvantage level index")
## Normality assumption
Qnorm rjack
